# Lumina Validation Patterns

## Base Validation Rules

Define `$validationRules` on the model with standard Laravel validation syntax. These rules apply to both store and update operations:

```php
protected $validationRules = [
    'title' => 'required|string|max:255',
    'body' => 'required|string',
    'status' => 'in:draft,published,archived',
    'priority' => 'integer|between:1,5',
    'category_id' => 'exists:categories,id',
];
```

## Simple Format for Store/Update Rules

`$validationRulesStore` and `$validationRulesUpdate` use a **simple format** -- just field names, not full rule definitions. They control which fields from `$validationRules` are active and add presence modifiers:

```php
// These field names reference keys from $validationRules
protected $validationRulesStore = [
    'title',       // Uses the 'required|string|max:255' rule from $validationRules
    'body',        // Uses the 'required|string' rule from $validationRules
    'category_id', // Uses the 'exists:categories,id' rule from $validationRules
];

protected $validationRulesUpdate = [
    'title',       // Same base rule, but applied on update
];
```

## Presence Modifiers

Prefix field names with `required:`, `nullable:`, or `sometimes:` to override the presence behavior:

```php
protected $validationRulesStore = [
    'title',              // Inherits presence from $validationRules (required)
    'required:body',      // Explicitly required on store
    'nullable:subtitle',  // Allowed to be null on store
    'sometimes:priority', // Only validated if present in the request
];

protected $validationRulesUpdate = [
    'sometimes:title',    // Only validated if included in the update payload
    'nullable:body',      // Can be set to null on update
];
```

## Full Override with Pipe

To completely replace the base rule for a specific operation, use the pipe `|` syntax:

```php
protected $validationRulesStore = [
    'title',
    'slug|required|string|unique:articles,slug', // Full override: ignores $validationRules for this field
];

protected $validationRulesUpdate = [
    'slug|sometimes|string|unique:articles,slug,{id}', // Different override for update
];
```

## Custom Validation Messages

```php
protected $validationRulesMessages = [
    'title.required' => 'A title is required for every article.',
    'body.required' => 'The article body cannot be empty.',
    'status.in' => 'Status must be one of: draft, published, archived.',
    'category_id.exists' => 'The selected category does not exist.',
];
```

## Role-Based Validation

For models where different roles can edit different fields, implement the `HasRoleBasedValidation` contract. Validation rules are keyed by role slug, and the `*` wildcard serves as a fallback for any role not explicitly listed:

```php
<?php

namespace App\Models;

use Illuminate\Database\Eloquent\Factories\HasFactory;
use Illuminate\Database\Eloquent\SoftDeletes;
use Lumina\LaravelApi\Traits\HasValidation;
use Lumina\LaravelApi\Traits\HidableColumns;
use Lumina\LaravelApi\Traits\BelongsToOrganization;
use Lumina\LaravelApi\Contracts\HasRoleBasedValidation;

class Article extends \Illuminate\Database\Eloquent\Model implements HasRoleBasedValidation
{
    use HasFactory;
    use SoftDeletes;
    use HasValidation;
    use HidableColumns;
    use BelongsToOrganization;

    protected $fillable = [
        'title',
        'slug',
        'body',
        'status',
        'featured',
        'author_id',
        'organization_id',
    ];

    // Base rules for all fields
    protected $validationRules = [
        'title' => 'required|string|max:255',
        'slug' => 'required|string|max:255|unique:articles,slug',
        'body' => 'required|string',
        'status' => 'required|in:draft,published,archived',
        'featured' => 'boolean',
    ];

    // Role-based store rules
    protected $validationRulesStore = [
        'admin' => [
            'title',
            'slug',
            'body',
            'status',
            'featured',   // Admins can set featured on creation
        ],
        'editor' => [
            'title',
            'slug',
            'body',
            'status',
            // Editors cannot set 'featured' on creation
        ],
        '*' => [
            'title',
            'body',
            // Default role: only title and body
        ],
    ];

    // Role-based update rules
    protected $validationRulesUpdate = [
        'admin' => [
            'sometimes:title',
            'sometimes:slug',
            'sometimes:body',
            'sometimes:status',
            'sometimes:featured',
        ],
        'editor' => [
            'sometimes:title',
            'sometimes:body',
            'sometimes:status',
        ],
        '*' => [
            'sometimes:title',
            'sometimes:body',
        ],
    ];

    /**
     * Return the current user's role slug for validation resolution.
     * This method is required by the HasRoleBasedValidation contract.
     */
    public function getRoleSlugForValidation(): string
    {
        $user = auth()->user();

        if (!$user) {
            return '*';
        }

        // Use the user's role in the current organization
        return $user->rolesInOrganization()?->first()?->slug ?? '*';
    }
}
```

## Key Behavior: Unlisted Fields Are Silently Ignored

Fields not listed in `$validationRulesStore` or `$validationRulesUpdate` are **silently ignored** -- they are stripped from the request before processing. They are NOT rejected with a validation error.

This means:
- If `featured` is not in the `editor` store rules, an editor sending `featured: true` will not get an error -- the field is simply dropped.
- This is a **security feature**: it prevents role escalation by silently discarding fields a role is not authorized to set.

```php
// If an editor sends: { title: "Hello", featured: true }
// Lumina processes: { title: "Hello" }
// The 'featured' field is silently stripped, not rejected.
```

## The * Wildcard

The `*` key is a **fallback** for any role not explicitly defined in the role-based arrays:

```php
protected $validationRulesStore = [
    'admin' => ['title', 'body', 'status', 'featured'],
    'editor' => ['title', 'body', 'status'],
    '*' => ['title', 'body'],  // Any other role (viewer, guest, etc.)
];
```

If the authenticated user's role is `viewer` and there is no `viewer` key, the `*` rules apply.

## DON'Ts

- **DO NOT** define full rule strings in `$validationRulesStore` or `$validationRulesUpdate` without the pipe prefix. The simple format expects field names only; use `|` to provide a full override.
- **DO NOT** assume unlisted fields will cause validation errors. They are silently ignored.
- **DO NOT** forget to implement `getRoleSlugForValidation()` when using the `HasRoleBasedValidation` contract.
- **DO NOT** mix simple format and role-based format in the same array. Use one or the other consistently.
